when expressed in heterologous cells produce GABA-activated chloride
channels, and the different subtypes express different pharmacological
properties. The distributions of mRNAs for the different GABAA receptor
polypeptides and their subtypes show significant brain regional variation
consistent with pharmacological and biochemical evidence for receptor
heterogeneity. Subpopulations of GABAA receptors with different cellular
and regional locations show differential sensitivity to GABA, to
modulators like steroids, to physiological regulation, to disease
