responsible for the cholesterol depletion mediated-increase in the
alphaC418W nAChR's macroscopic current. The present study suggests
that a substantial fraction of the alphaC418W nAChRs is located in
caveolin-1-positive domains, "trapped" in a non-activatable state,
and that membrane cholesterol depletion results in the relocation
of these receptors to the activatable pool. Co-fractionation and
co-immunoprecipitation of the alphaC418W nAChR and the membrane raft
protein caveolin-1 (cav1) support the notion that interactions at
lipid-exposed domains regulate the partition of the receptor into
membrane raft microdomains. These results have potential implications
as a novel mechanism to fine-tune cholinergic transmission in the
nervous system and in the pathogenesis associated to the alphaC418W
nAChR.},
author = {B{\'{a}}ez-Pag{\'{a}}n, Carlos and Mart$\backslash$'inez-Ortiz, Yaiza and Otero-Cruz, Jos{\'{e}} and Salgado-Villanueva, Iris and Vel{\'{a}}zquez, Guermarie and Ortiz-Acevedo, Alejandro and Quesada, Orestes and Silva, Walter and Lasalde-Dominicci, Jos{\'{e}}},
